    <h1 style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      Having created 30,000+ images using AI<span class="p"
        >, I&#39;ve run a ton of experiments.</span
      >
    </h1>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      Among them, I&#39;ve come to four core principles you should apply when
      prompting to create visuals for better results.
    </p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 3pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      Disclaimer though: It’s early days still. Like so much about AI, I don’t
      know for a fact everything here is absolutely true.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      I doubt even the people who designed these systems know. That&#39;s sort
      of what makes AI cool. It&#39;s like an unknown space, just waiting to be
      explored.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      What I can tell you for certain is that
      <b>poorly written prompts = waiting more often</b>.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      And depending on what tool you’re using, bad prompts don&#39;t just cost
      you time, they might cost you money.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 261%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      So the fewer renders you need to perform to get to a result you like, the
      better. Here&#39;s how to get great results, often even on your first try.
    </p>

    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      Just these four ideas will vastly improve your results.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <ol id="l1">
      <li data-list-text="1.">
        <p
          class="s4"
          style="padding-left: 18pt; text-indent: -13pt; text-align: left"
        >
          Follow the right order of information
        </p>
        <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        <p
          style="
            padding-left: 5pt;
            text-indent: 0pt;
            line-height: 130%;
            text-align: left;
          "
        >
          One of the cardinal rules of image prompting is that the words toward
          the beginning of the prompt have a stronger impact than the words at
          the end.
        </p>
        <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        <p
          style="
            padding-left: 5pt;
            text-indent: 0pt;
            line-height: 130%;
            text-align: left;
          "
        >
          Taking this a step further, the general order of information that
          seems to work well in all of the current AI art tools I&#39;ve used
          is:
        </p>
        <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        <ol id="l2">
          <li data-list-text="1.">
            <p
              style="
                padding-top: 10pt;

                text-indent: -16pt;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              The kind of image you want
            </p>
          </li>
          <li data-list-text="2.">
            <p
              style="
                padding-top: 7pt;
                padding-left: 31pt;
                text-indent: -16pt;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              The subject of the image
            </p>
          </li>
          <li data-list-text="3.">
            <p
              style="
                padding-top: 7pt;
                padding-left: 31pt;
                text-indent: -16pt;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              Details of the main subject
            </p>
          </li>
          <li data-list-text="4.">
            <p

                padding-top: 7pt;

                text-indent: -16pt;
                text-align: left;
              "

      style="

        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      AI art models are trained by classifying images. Basically, a computer
      looks at the image and guesses what’s in it according to natural language.
      And another computer that&#39;s been trained to help, tells the first
      computer if it&#39;s right or if it&#39;s wrong. And sometimes humans help
      too.
    </p>

      style="

        text-align: left;

      Because...

        text-align: left;

      AI ‘thinks’ and what various words can mean.

        <h1 style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">

            text-indent: 0pt;
            line-height: 130%;
            text-align: left;
          "

        <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        <p
          style="
            padding-left: 5pt;
            text-indent: 0pt;
            line-height: 130%;
            text-align: left;
          "

        </p>
        <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        <h1
          style="
            padding-left: 5pt;
            text-indent: 0pt;
            line-height: 261%;
            text-align: left;
          "
        >

          <span class="p"
            >is an expression of beauty that is generally applied to all people.
            It’s somewhat genderless. Attractive can also be used to describe a
            few other things too, like the terms of a deal can be
            attractive.</span

        </h1>
        <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        <h1 style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">

        <p
          style="
            padding-top: 3pt;
            padding-left: 5pt;
            text-indent: 0pt;
            line-height: 130%;
            text-align: left;
          "
        >

        </p>
        <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>

            text-indent: 0pt;

        <p

            text-indent: 0pt;
            line-height: 261%;
            text-align: left;

    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 2pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #d06464;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >a gorgeous girl</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 4pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      To avoid making pictures of children, don&#39;t prompt with your keywords.
      Instead,
    </p>
    <p style="padding-left: 2pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #d06464;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >a gorgeous female</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 4pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      prompt . Girl can skew very childish.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 10pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      That is, unless you have a solid negative prompt in place.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 10pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      This brings us to positive and negative prompts.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <ol id="l11">
      <li data-list-text="2.">
        <p
          class="s4"
          style="padding-left: 18pt; text-indent: -13pt; text-align: left"
        >
          Include the right negatives
        </p>
        <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
          Most AI image generators use a combination of two prompts:
        </p>
        <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
        <ul id="l12">
          <li data-list-text="•">
            <p
              style="
                padding-top: 4pt;
                padding-left: 31pt;
                text-indent: -12pt;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              Positive prompt = what’s in the image?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li data-list-text="•">
            <p
              style="
                padding-top: 8pt;
                padding-left: 31pt;
                text-indent: -12pt;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              Negative prompt = what’s not there?
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p
              style="
                padding-top: 4pt;
                padding-bottom: 2pt;
                padding-left: 5pt;
                text-indent: 0pt;
                line-height: 261%;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              Here&#39;s a simplistic example. Compare the following.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p
              class="s5"
              style="
                padding-top: 7pt;
                padding-left: 23pt;
                text-indent: 0pt;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              : a hot dog
            </p>
            <p
              class="s5"
              style="
                padding-top: 4pt;
                padding-left: 23pt;
                text-indent: 0pt;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              : (nothing in the negative prompt section)
            </p>
            <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <h1
              style="
                padding-top: 11pt;
                padding-left: 5pt;
                text-indent: 0pt;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              &quot;A hot dog&quot;
              <span class="p">- Rendering by Midjourney v4 (Feb 6, 2023)</span>
            </h1>
            <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
              <span
                ><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
                  <tr>
                    <td>
                      <img
                        width="739"
                        height="185"
                        src="data:image/jpg;base64,"
                      />
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>
                      <img
                        width="739"
                        height="185"
                        src="data:image/jpg;base64,"
                      />
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>
                      <img
                        width="739"
                        height="185"
                        src="data:image/jpg;base64,"
                      />
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>
                      <img
                        width="739"
                        height="184"
                        src="data:image/jpg;base64,"
                      />
                    </td>
                  </tr></table
              ></span>
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
              Now look at this one.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p
              class="s5"
              style="
                padding-top: 7pt;
                padding-left: 23pt;
                text-indent: 0pt;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              : a hot dog
            </p>
            <p
              class="s5"
              style="
                padding-top: 4pt;
                padding-left: 23pt;
                text-indent: 0pt;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              : fire, smoke, animals
            </p>
            <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <h1
              style="
                padding-top: 11pt;
                padding-left: 5pt;
                text-indent: 0pt;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              &quot;a hot dog --no fire, smoke, animals&quot; - Rendering by
              Midjourney v4 (Feb 6, 2023)
            </h1>
            <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
              <span
                ><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
                  <tr>
                    <td>
                      <img
                        width="739"
                        height="185"
                        src="data:image/jpg;base64,"
                      />
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>
                      <img
                        width="739"
                        height="185"
                        src="data:image/jpg;base64,"
                      />
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>
                      <img
                        width="739"
                        height="185"
                        src="data:image/jpg;base64,"
                      />
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>
                      <img
                        width="739"
                        height="184"
                        src="data:image/jpg;base64,"
                      />
                    </td>
                  </tr></table
              ></span>
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
              Midjourney didn&#39;t make a perfect hog dog in the second one
              version, I know.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p
              style="
                padding-left: 5pt;
                text-indent: 0pt;
                line-height: 130%;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              But we&#39;re A LOT closer to what we&#39;re looking for. If I
              wanted to continue trying to get a perfect hotdog, I&#39;m in a
              much better spot.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
              See, words have nuanced meanings.
            </p>
            <p
              style="
                padding-top: 3pt;
                padding-left: 5pt;
                text-indent: 0pt;
                line-height: 130%;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              It seems obvious to us humans because we innately understand that
              people don&#39;t say, &quot;hot dog&quot; and mean a dog that is
              on fire.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p
              style="
                padding-left: 5pt;
                text-indent: 0pt;
                line-height: 130%;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              But with AI, the magic figurer-outer goes out into its pre-trained
              model, looks at word-image associations, and brings back what it
              thinks you want based on the data.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p
              style="
                padding-left: 5pt;
                text-indent: 0pt;
                line-height: 130%;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              It&#39;s computer friend that helped it train on the meanings of
              words and images never explained that some dogs are indeed, not
              hot in that way.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
            <p
              style="
                padding-left: 5pt;
                text-indent: 0pt;
                line-height: 130%;
                text-align: left;
              "
            >
              Now that we understand both the full meaning of words and negative
              prompting, the next step is to fix a major issue that most people
              make negative prompts.
            </p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li data-list-text="3.">
        <p
          class="s4"
          style="padding-left: 18pt; text-indent: -13pt; text-align: left"
        >
          Unloading your negatives
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      Here’s a typical style of prompt that I see all the time:
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      class="s5"
      style="
        padding-top: 7pt;
        padding-left: 18pt;
        text-indent: 5pt;
        line-height: 139%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      : extremely detailed, full body color photo, Albert Einstein, young man,
      background laboratory, film grain, skin details, high detailed skin
      texture, 8k, hdr, dslr
    </p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      class="s5"
      style="
        padding-top: 7pt;
        padding-left: 18pt;
        text-indent: 5pt;
        line-height: 139%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      : cgi, 3d, render, sketch, cartoon, drawing, anime, deformed, bad anatomy,
      disfigured, poorly drawn face, mutation, mutated, distorted hands,
      deformed, extra limb, ugly,
    </p>
    <p
      class="s5"
      style="
        padding-left: 18pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 10pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      disgusting, poorly drawn hands, missing limb, floating limbs, disconnected
      limbs,
    </p>
    <p
      class="s5"
      style="
        padding-top: 4pt;
        padding-left: 18pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 132%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      malformed hands, mutated hands and fingers, distorted hands, amputation,
      missing hands, doubled face, double hands, b&amp;w, black and white,
      sepia, black and white photo, blur
    </p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 11pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      What you can see is that, on the positive side, we have a series of image
      tags, each separated by a comma.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      There is no established relationship between the tags. This is how 90%+ of
      people write prompts I think.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      When confronted with this style of prompt, the AI model has to infer
      everything based on the order of the words (toward the front is more
      important) and the relationships between those words.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      We&#39;ll fix the positive side in a sec, but first we have to deal with
      the dumpster fire of a negative prompt.
    </p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 3pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      So much restriction! And for what.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      So before we talk about word order and commas, let’s unload the negative
      prompt.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <h1 style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      How to unload your negative prompts
    </h1>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      Here&#39;s what I&#39;m going to teach you to do:
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <h1
      style="
        padding-top: 11pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      ORIGINAL negative prompt
    </h1>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      class="s5"
      style="
        padding-top: 7pt;
        padding-left: 18pt;
        text-indent: 5pt;
        line-height: 139%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      : cgi, 3d, render, sketch, cartoon, drawing, anime, deformed, bad anatomy,
      disfigured, poorly drawn face, mutation, mutated, distorted hands,
      deformed, extra limb, ugly,
    </p>
    <p
      class="s5"
      style="
        padding-left: 18pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 10pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      disgusting, poorly drawn hands, missing limb, floating limbs, disconnected
      limbs,
    </p>
    <p
      class="s5"
      style="
        padding-top: 4pt;
        padding-left: 18pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 132%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      malformed hands, mutated hands and fingers, distorted hands, amputation,
      missing hands, doubled face, double hands, b&amp;w, black and white,
      sepia, black and white photo, blur
    </p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <h1
      style="
        padding-top: 4pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      REVISED negative prompt
    </h1>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      class="s5"
      style="
        padding-top: 7pt;
        padding-left: 23pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      : cartoon, plastic, arachnid, desaturated, blurred
    </p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 11pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      The technique here is to avoid overloading the negative prompt with too
      many variables where it sort of blindfolds the AI to all sorts of good
      image data that it could otherwise make use of.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      These 5 words were selected very carefully.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 10pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      For example, by negative prompting for
    </p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 10pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      and
    </p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 10pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      , we attempt to eliminate any illustration
    </p>
    <p style="padding-left: 2pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #d06464;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >cartoon</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p style="padding-left: 2pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #d06464;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >plastic</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 4pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      (cartoon) or 3D rendered style (plastic-looking skin) without also losing
      access to other information that might be helpful.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: justify;
      "
    >
      By not removing drawings, anime, sketches, etc, the model has a richer set
      of inspiration to drawn on for scenes, poses, etc. If a shot still comes
      out looking like not-a-photograph, we can consider adding more to the
      positive or negative side.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: justify">
      Dealing with bad anatomy.
    </p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 3pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      With recent updates to most models, you also don&#39;t need to battle very
      hard against bad anatomy unless it&#39;s really a problem. Not like you
      used to, anyway.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 2pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #d06464;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >arachnid</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 4pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      Here, stands in for all the bad anatomy keywords.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 10pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      Arachnids have multiple non-human limbs and extra eyes, after all. If we
      want to avoid ugly, mutated-looking bodies, let&#39;s start by avoiding
      anything spider-like.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; line-height: 13pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #333;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >Note: If you still get bad anatomy, sure, drop additional words in, but
        be cautious.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; line-height: 13pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #333;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >Think about it.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; line-height: 13pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #333;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >If you want good hand anatomy, it seems illogical to negative prompt
        “extra hands” which would</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="padding-top: 4pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #333;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >also eliminate many pictures of proper hands from the data the AI
        explores.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; line-height: 13pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #333;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >What would be a keyword to fix your problem that doesn&#39;t include
        the name of the thing you want in</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="padding-top: 4pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #333;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >the picture?</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      Continuing on...
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 2pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #d06464;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >Desaturated</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p style="padding-left: 2pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #d06464;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >black and white photo</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 10pt;
        padding-left: 84pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      is better than for a similar reason.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 10pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      We want all photos and colors to help our AI, so we express the concept of
      black and white in a totally different way.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      If you think about how important the words black, white, and photo are,
      you can see why we&#39;d want to avoid prompting against it. They probably
      show up in training data everywhere.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      As you can see, when over-used, negative prompts behave like static for
      the language model, cutting off otherwise useful data because of inferred
      relationships between words.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      By unloading negative prompts, you get more specific about what you don’t
      want and enable the AI to retrieve what you do, making full use of the
      model&#39;s capabilities.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      Now that we&#39;re accidentally limiting our good data, let&#39;s help the
      AI understand exactly what we want to see.
    </p>
    <p
      class="s4"
      style="
        padding-top: 4pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      4: Using joining words and commas
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      While we don&#39;t usually think of an AI art tool as a large language
      model, many of the lessons from tools like GPT-3 and ChatGPT still apply
      here.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      The language is <u>ever</u>y<u>thing</u>.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      And in language, commas act as a firm separator between linked ideas. What
      is on one side of a comma is different from what is on the other side.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 261%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      Using the same example from above, we can easily improve the original
      prompt for better results. Let&#39;s look at its original positive side
      again to refresh our memory.
    </p>
    <h1
      style="
        padding-top: 3pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      ORIGINAL positive prompt
    </h1>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      class="s5"
      style="
        padding-top: 7pt;
        padding-left: 18pt;
        text-indent: 5pt;
        line-height: 139%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      : extremely detailed, full body color photo, Albert Einstein, young man,
      background laboratory, film grain, skin details, high detailed skin
      texture, 8k, hdr, dslr
    </p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 11pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      All of the ideas are separated by commas, with
      <b>very little grouping </b>as to what belongs with what.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      Is this supposed to be a picture of Albert Einstein next to a young man
      who is holding a DSLR camera, perhaps?
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      Probably not, but we&#39;re making the AI infer all that, which means
      we&#39;re not as likely to get an amazing result. At best, we probably get
      an average image back.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      I mean, look at my first test image from Midjourney. All old guys and one
      shirtless guy with random marker drawings on his body? Nothing in a
      laboratory at all?
    </p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        ><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">

    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      We need to fix this.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      Below is my new prompt, and I&#39;ll break down what changes I made.
    </p>

    <p

        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      But first let me show you the images. There are still some issues that

    </p>

    <h1

        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      REVISED positive prompt
    </h1>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      class="s5"
      style="
        padding-top: 7pt;

        text-indent: 5pt;

    </p>
    <p style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 11pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      Analyze the placement of these words:
    </p>

    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 10pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      Using commas and joining words, each main idea of the image is grouped
      together in one comma-separated clause, and all objects and adjectives are
      associated correctly with each other using natural language.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p style="padding-left: 2pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #d06464;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >full body color photo of Albert Einstein as a young man</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 4pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      From the phrase, , there can be no confusion
    </p>
    <p style="padding-left: 2pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #d06464;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >taken</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #d06464;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >with a DSLR</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 4pt;
        padding-left: 78pt;
        text-indent: -73pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      of whether I want a picture of Albert Einstein AND a young man or AS a
      young man. Likewise, clarifies whether he is holding a DSLR camera or the
      picture was taken with one.
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      Note though, that according to our original prompt structure from the very
      beginning of this guide, I use the practice of adding smaller details on
      style at the end. This is because we want the AI to be very clear about
      the main subject.
    </p>
    <p style="padding-left: 3pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #d06464;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "

      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 3pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      To make my follow-along details as accurate as possible, I re-referenced
      the photo when I wrote
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #d06464;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >the photograph showing film grain and natural skin with details and
        texture</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 4pt;
        padding-left: 406pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      .
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 4pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      (Attentive readers will notice that
    </p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 4pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      and
    </p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 4pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      still missed the mark, so we may
    </p>
    <p style="padding-left: 2pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #d06464;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >color photo</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p style="padding-left: 2pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      <span
        style="
          color: #d06464;
          font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
          font-style: normal;
          font-weight: normal;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-size: 12pt;
        "
        >--no desaturated</span
      >
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left" />
    <p
      style="
        padding-top: 4pt;
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
      need to prompt against sepia tones or isolate &quot;color photo&quot; in
      quotes to get the best result. That&#39;s how AI works. You&#39;re always
      going to need to do a bit of experimentation.)
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p class="s4" style="padding-left: 5pt; text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left">
      Wrap up
    </p>
    <p style="text-indent: 0pt; text-align: left"><br /></p>
    <p
      style="
        padding-left: 5pt;
        text-indent: 0pt;
        line-height: 130%;
        text-align: left;
      "
    >
